english:
  title: Record of the Dragon-Fishing Pavilion
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A friend of mine, Min Gyeon, visited me after several years away. His appearance and manner of speech were so clear and refined, so spare and unpretentious, that he seemed like a transcendent immortal—I did not recognize him at first. Puzzled, I asked him: "Have you recently devoted yourself to the books of the sages? Have you kept company with men of virtue and moral cultivation? Or have you found joy in dwelling at home and performing acts of goodness? Why does your bearing differ so greatly from before?"

    Min Gyeon replied: "I have no particular ambition or undertaking. Simply, to the west of my dwelling, along the banks of the great river, there stands a fishing pavilion. Behind it, mountains rise and then break away; before it, the fields open wide and stretch endlessly. When I gaze down, I am reminded to guard against the perils of deep waters; when I look up, I am moved to contemplate heights ever greater. I have spent my days coming and going in that place—casting my line and catching fish, drawing my knife to prepare them, drawing clear water from the stream to brew wine. Once I have eaten my fill and grown pleasantly drunk, my contentment is complete. This is all my days contain. Even when summer rains swell the river and its waters overflow—sweeping away the fields I had planted and tilled, leaving no secure dwelling—I endure on coarse rice alone, yet dare not abandon this place for another. It is the joy of the fishing pavilion that keeps me bound here. I myself did not notice how my manner had changed, as you perceive it."

    Then I understood: the place where one dwells has the power to transform one's spirit. Thus it is that princes and great lords carry themselves with the fullness of worldly success, while mountain hermits bear the hardship of refinement in their hearts. Each man's spirit is shaped by the station he occupies. Min Gyeon's transformation owes everything to this pavilion. In this I came to know that when Yan Ziling dared to slight the Son of Heaven, it was surely with the aid of those Seven-Mile Rapids where he fished.¹ Min Gyeon had likewise discovered in his river dwelling a kindred spirit.

    Min Gyeon then asked that I give the pavilion a new name. I proposed "The Dragon-Fishing Pavilion." He objected: "One fishes for fish to have them for food—but what use is a dragon?" I replied: "Your vision is too narrow. In ancient times there were those who raised dragons, and those who learned to butcher them. Yet whether we raise or butcher, who would discard such creatures? A dragon, after all, is merely a great fish. With a great enough line, why distinguish between fish and dragon?" And so I persuaded him, and the pavilion was formally named "The Dragon-Fishing Pavilion."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yan Ziling (嚴子陵): A legendary recluse of the Han dynasty who famously refused an emperor''s invitation to office, choosing instead a life of fishing and solitude. His Seven-Mile Rapids became legendary as a place where spirit transcends worldly power.'
